======================================================================
PART 1: THE PETERSEN GRAPH — ANATOMY OF 10 = 2·5
======================================================================

Petersen graph P = K(5,2)
Vertices (10): 2-subsets of [5]
   0: {0, 1}
   1: {0, 2}
   2: {0, 3}
   3: {0, 4}
   4: {1, 2}
   5: {1, 3}
   6: {1, 4}
   7: {2, 3}
   8: {2, 4}
   9: {3, 4}

Edges (15): pairs of disjoint 2-subsets
Degree: 3 (3-regular)

Petersen graph invariants:
  Vertices: 10 = 2·5 = KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂)
  Edges: 15 = C(6,2) = 15
  Degree: 3 = KEY₂
  Girth: 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂
  Diameter: 2 = KEY₁
  Chromatic number: 3 = KEY₂
  Chromatic index: 4 (NOT 3 — Petersen is a snark!)
  Independence number: 4 = KEY₁²
  Clique number: 2 = KEY₁ (triangle-free)
  |Aut(P)| = |S₅| = 120 = |BI| (binary icosahedral!)

Kneser structure K(5,2):
  C(5,2) = 10 vertices
  C(3,2) = 3 edges per vertex
  C(10,2) - 15 = 30 non-edges
  Non-edges = 30 = h(E₈)!

Complement of Petersen (Johnson graph J(5,2)):
  Edges: 30 = 30 = h(E₈)
  Degree: 10 - 1 - 3 = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)
  This graph is the line graph of K₅!

L(K₅) = J(5,2) = complement of Petersen
  K₅ has 5 vertices, C(5,2) = 10 edges
  Each vertex of K₅ has degree 4 = KEY₁²
  L(K₅) is 6-regular = 6-regular

======================================================================
PART 2: THE T=10 MOAT — WHERE TOURNAMENTS EXPLODE
======================================================================

Tournament counts T(n) = A000568:
  T( 1) =            1
  T( 2) =            1
  T( 3) =            2
  T( 4) =            4
  T( 5) =           12
  T( 6) =           56
  T( 7) =          456
  T( 8) =         6880
  T( 9) =       191536
  T(10) =      9733056

Growth ratios T(n+1)/T(n):
  T(2)/T(1) =         1.00
  T(3)/T(2) =         2.00
  T(4)/T(3) =         2.00
  T(5)/T(4) =         3.00
  T(6)/T(5) =         4.67
  T(7)/T(6) =         8.14
  T(8)/T(7) =        15.09
  T(9)/T(8) =        27.84
  T(10)/T(9) =        50.82

The T=10 moat:
  T(10) = 9,733,056 ≈ 10^6.99
  T(10)/T(9) = 50.82
  T(9)/T(8) = 27.84
  T(8)/T(7) = 15.09

  The growth accelerates: 15.08 → 27.83 → 50.82
  Each ratio roughly doubles — exponential acceleration!

Why T=10 is the moat:
  Edges: C(10,2) = 45 = 45
  Labeled tournaments: 2^45 = 35,184,372,088,832
  |S₁₀| = 10! = 3,628,800
  2^45/10! = 9,695,870 ≈ T(10)
  At n=10, almost ALL labeled tournaments are asymmetric!

The 2·5 structure:
  10 = C(5,2) = #edges of K₅
  5 = KEY₁+KEY₂ = #Platonic solids = #exceptional Lie groups
  So T(10) counts tournaments on C(5,2) vertices
  Equivalently: tournaments on the vertex set of the Petersen graph!

======================================================================
PART 3: PETERSEN AND THE EXCEPTIONAL GROUPS
======================================================================

|Aut(Petersen)| = |S₅| = 120 = |BI| (binary icosahedral)

The binary icosahedral group maps to E₈ via McKay!
So the Petersen graph's symmetry group IS the McKay group for E₈!

Petersen graph spectrum:
  λ₁ = 3 (multiplicity 1) = KEY₂ = degree
  λ₂ = 1 (multiplicity 5) = unit
  λ₃ = -2 (multiplicity 4) = -KEY₁

  Eigenvalues: {{3, 1, -2}} = {{KEY₂, 1, -KEY₁}}
  The tournament keys appear as the EXTREME eigenvalues!
  Spectral gap: 3 - 1 = 2 = KEY₁
  λ_max + λ_min = 3 + (-2) = 1 = unit
  λ_max · |λ_min| = 3 · 2 = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)

  Eigenvalue multiplicities: 1, 5, 4
    1 = unit
    5 = KEY₁+KEY₂ = #exceptional groups
    4 = KEY₁² = independence number of Petersen
    Sum: 1+5+4 = 10 = #vertices ✓

Characteristic polynomial evaluation:
  χ_P(0) = det(-A) = (-3)·(-1)⁵·(2)⁴ = 48
  |det(A)| = 48 = |BO| (binary octahedral → E₇!)

  χ_P(KEY₁) = χ_P(2) = (2-3)·1⁵·4⁴ = -256 = -KEY₁⁸
  |χ_P(KEY₁)| = 256 = 2⁸ = KEY₁^rank(E₈)
  χ_P(KEY₂) = χ_P(3) = 0 (KEY₂ is an eigenvalue!)

SUMMARY OF PETERSEN ↔ EXCEPTIONAL CONNECTIONS:
  |Aut| = 120 = |BI| → E₈ (McKay)
  |det(A)| = 48 = |BO| → E₇ (McKay)
  Eigenvalues = {KEY₂, 1, -KEY₁}
  |χ(KEY₁)| = KEY₁^rank(E₈)
  Complement has 30 = h(E₈) edges
  Complement is 6-regular: degree = h(G₂)

