PART 4: THE INDEPENDENCE POLYNOMIAL OF THE PETERSEN GRAPH
======================================================================

Independence polynomial I(P, x) = 1 + 10x^1 + 30x^2 + 30x^3 + 5x^4

  I(P, KEY₁) = I(P, 2) = 461
  I(P, KEY₂) = I(P, 3) = 1516
  I(P, -1) = -4

  I(2) = 461 = 461
  I(3) = 1516 = 2·2·379
  I(-1) = -4

Chromatic polynomial of the Petersen graph:
  P(0) = 240 = dim(so(16))? = 2⁴·3·5
  P(1) = 79
  P(2) = 320
  P(3) = 1293
  P(4) = 18688
  P(5) = 358115
  P(6) = 3957504
  P(7) = 28029745

  P(KEY₂) = P(3) = 1293 = h(E₆) = h(F₄)!
  The Petersen graph has exactly h(E₆) proper 3-colorings!

Chromatic polynomial coefficients (ascending):
  [240, -1500, 3740, -5025, 4550, -2922, 1360, -455, 105, -15, 1]
  Leading term: t^10 (as expected for 10 vertices)
  Constant term: 240 = 2⁴·3·5 = KEY₁⁴·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)
  |coefficient of t| = 1500 = 2²·3·5³
  |coefficient of t²| = 3740 = 2²·5·11·17

======================================================================
PART 5: PETERSEN AS TOURNAMENT CONFLICT GRAPH?
======================================================================

Can the Petersen graph be CG(T)?

Requirements for CG(T) = Petersen:
  - 10 odd directed cycles in the tournament
  - Each cycle conflicts with exactly 3 others
  - No three cycles mutually conflict (triangle-free)
  - Shortest conflict cycle has length 5

If Petersen = CG(T):
  H(T) = I(P, 2) = 461
  I(-1) = -4

  α_k sequence: [1, 10, 30, 30, 5, 0]
  α_0=1, α_1=10, α_2=30, α_3=30, α_4=5

  Number of max independent sets (size 4): 5
  5 = KEY₁+KEY₂ = #Platonic solids = #exceptional groups

======================================================================
PART 6: THE DOUBLE-5 STRUCTURE
======================================================================

The DOUBLE-5 decomposition:

  The 10 vertices split into 5 complementary pairs:

  5 pairs, each summing to {0,1,2,3,4}
  Two vertices in a pair are ALWAYS adjacent (disjoint subsets)
  The 5 pairs form a perfect matching!

Petersen graph Hamiltonian properties:
  NOT Hamiltonian (no Hamilton cycle)
  But has Hamilton paths
  This non-Hamiltonicity is KEY — makes it a 'snark'

The DOUBLE-5 in Lie theory:
  5 exceptional Lie groups: G₂, F₄, E₆, E₇, E₈
  5 Platonic solids: tet, cube, oct, dodec, icos
  The McKay correspondence pairs them:
    G₂ — (standalone, no Platonic)
    F₄ — (standalone, no Platonic)
    E₆ ↔ Tetrahedron (BT, order 24)
    E₇ ↔ Cube/Octahedron (BO, order 48)
    E₈ ↔ Dodecahedron/Icosahedron (BI, order 120)

  But there are 5 Platonic solids and only 3 McKay pairs!
  The 'missing' two Platonic solids (cube+octahedron = one pair)
  gives: Tet, Cube/Oct, Dodec/Icos = 3 McKay pairs
  Plus: G₂ and F₄ are the 'extra' 2 exceptional groups
  Total: 5 = 3 + 2 = KEY₂ + KEY₁

======================================================================
PART 7: THE PETERSEN GRAPH AND THE NUMBER 10
======================================================================

The many lives of 10 = 2·5:
  C(5,2) = 10 (2-subsets of 5-set)
  T(5) = 12, but T(4) + T(5) = 16... no
  dim(so(5)) = dim(sp(4)) = 10 (B₂≅C₂)
  #edges of K₅ = 10
  #vertices of Petersen = 10
  h(D₆) = 10
  E₈ branch sum: 2+3+5 = 10

10 as 'shifted 1':
  In base 10: 10 = '10' = the 'next 1'
  In base 2: 10 = 1010₂
  In base 3: 10 = 101₃
  In base 5: 10 = 20₅ = KEY₁·0 + KEY₁ = 2·5
  In base 9: 10 = 11₉ (shifted 1 in base KEY₂²)

10 in the tournament recurrence a(n) = 5a(n-1) - 6a(n-2):
  10 = KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂) — the product of root and trace
  In the tournament poly z²-5z+6:
  f(10) = 100 - 50 + 6 = 56 = T(6) = dim(V_E₇)!

  f(10) = 10² - 5·10 + 6 = 56
  T(6) = 56 = dim(V_E₇)
  f(2·5) = f(KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂)) = T(KEY₁·KEY₂)

  THIS IS AMAZING:
  The tournament polynomial evaluated at 10 gives T(6)!
  f(10) = 56 = T(6) = dim(minuscule E₇) = C(8,3)

  f evaluated at key numbers:
    f( 1) =      2 = T(3), KEY₁
    f( 2) =      0 = root!
    f( 3) =      0 = root!
    f( 4) =      2 = T(3), KEY₁
    f( 5) =      6 = h(G₂)
    f( 6) =     12 = T(5), h(E₆)
    f( 7) =     20
    f( 8) =     30 = h(E₈)
    f( 9) =     42
    f(10) =     56 = T(6), dim(V_E₇)
    f(11) =     72
    f(12) =     90
    f(18) =    240
    f(30) =    756

======================================================================
PART 8: THE PETERSEN GRAPH IN TOURNAMENT THEORY
======================================================================

Tournaments on the Petersen vertex set:
  C(10,2) = 45 arcs = 15 (Petersen edges) + 30 (non-edges)
  15 = C(6,2)
  30 = h(E₈)
  45 = C(10,2) = C(KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂), KEY₁)

Petersen complement pairs and tournament structure:
  Each complement pair {S, S̄} in the Petersen graph
  corresponds to a partition of [5] into two 2-subsets + remainder
  Orienting the 5 matching edges gives 2⁵ = 32 patterns

  2⁵ = 32 = KEY₁^(KEY₁+KEY₂)
  32 is the number of labeled tournaments on 5 vertices (2^C(5,2)/C(5,2))
  Wait: 2^C(5,2) = 2^10 = 1024 labeled tournaments on 5 vertices
  But 32 = 2^5 is just the matching orientations

======================================================================
PART 9: THE RECURRENCE VIEW — 10 AND 11 AS SHIFTED ONES
======================================================================

10 and 11 as recurrence landmarks:

  In base b, '10' = b and '11' = b+1
  In the tournament recurrence (base = KEY₁·KEY₂ = 6):
  '10₆' = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)
  '11₆' = 7 = KEY₁²+KEY₂ = rank(E₇)

  In base KEY₁+KEY₂ = 5:
  '10₅' = 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂
  '11₅' = 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = h(G₂)

  In base KEY₁·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂) = 30:
  '10₃₀' = 30 = h(E₈)
  '11₃₀' = 31 = h(E₈)+1 (Mersenne prime!)

The 10-11 shift in Lie exponents:
  10 = h(D₆), NOT an E₈ exponent (divisible by 5)
  11 = UNIVERSAL E-exponent (in E₆, E₇, E₈)
  The shift 10→11 crosses the sieve boundary!
  10 is on the TOURNAMENT side (÷ by 2 and 5)
  11 is on the EXPONENT side (coprime to 30)

  This is the essence of the complementary sieve:
  10 and 11 are consecutive but on OPPOSITE sides
  10 encodes tournament structure (2·5)
  11 encodes Lie exponents (2³+3)

======================================================================
PART 10: f(10) = 56 — THE CROWN JEWEL
======================================================================

THE EQUATION: f(10) = 56

  f(z) = z² - 5z + 6 = (z-2)(z-3)
  f(10) = (10-2)(10-3) = 8·7 = 56
  = rank(E₈) · rank(E₇)
  = dim(minuscule E₇)
  = T(6) = number of tournaments on 6 vertices
  = C(8,3) = C(rank(E₈), KEY₂)

  AND: 10 = #vertices of the Petersen graph
         = C(5,2) = edges of K₅
         = KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂)

  So: f(#vertices(Petersen)) = T(KEY₁·KEY₂)
      f(C(5,2)) = T(6)
      (10-KEY₁)(10-KEY₂) = T(KEY₁·KEY₂)
      8 · 7 = 56

f(n) = T(m) solutions:
  f(4) = 2 = T(3)
  f(6) = 12 = T(5)
  f(10) = 56 = T(6)

  f(4) = 2 = T(3)
  f(6) = 12 = T(5)
  f(10) = 56 = T(6)

  The arguments: 4, 6, 10
  Differences: 6-4=2=KEY₁, 10-6=4=KEY₁²
  The outputs: T(3), T(5), T(6)
  T-arguments: 3, 5, 6 = KEY₂, KEY₁+KEY₂, KEY₁·KEY₂

THE PATTERN:
  f(KEY₁²) = T(KEY₂)
  f(KEY₁·KEY₂) = T(KEY₁+KEY₂)
  f(KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂)) = T(KEY₁·KEY₂)

  The argument-to-T mapping:
  KEY₁² → KEY₂
  KEY₁·KEY₂ → KEY₁+KEY₂
  KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂) → KEY₁·KEY₂
  The T-index ROTATES through the (2,3,5) expressions!
